Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

Red Wine dataset contains 1599 observations & 13 variable

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The “quality”" of the wine

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your into your feature(s) of interest?

Alcohol: the rate of alcohol in the wine in this dataset

volatile acidity: the amount in the wine,“flavor: vinegar taste”

citric acid: quantitie in wine, “flavor: freshness”

Quality: as we see above the majority are “Average”.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

Wine Levels (Good,Aveage,Bad)

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?  Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form the data? If so, why did you do this?

No, I have not done any tidy or adjust to data. There is Right-Skewed & Normally distributed plots. I only transform the quality rating into ordered levels.

Bivariate Plots Section

Correlation:

  • alcohol (positive correlation with quality )
  • volatile acidity (negative correlation with quality)
  • citric acid (positive correlation with quality )
  • sulphates (positive correlation with quality )
  • Density (negative correlation with quality & positive correlation with fixed acidity )

  • Density (negative correlation with quality & positive correlation with fixed acidity ) # Multivariate Plots Section

In this section we are going to create a few multivariate plots to investigate more complex interactions between the variables that are most related to quality of the wine. Then we willcreate some mathematical models.

  • Negative correlation between alcohol and density

  • Positive correlation between fixed acidity & Density which mean the acid make the wine more intense

-Positive correlation between critic acid and fixed acidity

  • Negative correlation between critic acid and volatile acidity

  • The correlation is low between pH & volatile acidity

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

The majority in this dataset (more than 1000) are an average qualitdy which is not actually lead us to analyze the good quality or what is the real features that may strongly affect it directly. So we can take the majortiy of the analysis here for the average quality red wines beacuse it is limited dataset.

Plot Two

Description Two

Alcohol & Quality Boxplot show the great impact of alcohol on the quality, as we say before it increase the wine quality, therefore, in this plot we can see the quality is normally distributed because the correspond in mean and median. so we can say that the median high value means that alcohol is also high.

Plot Three

Description Three

The above plot show that the increasing in both alcohol & sulphates together produce better quality wine

Reflection

First, it difficult project since it is requires a lot of knowledge about wine to analyze this dataset the majority of my time goes to the reading about the wine and the R programing langauge is new to me.

Also as I said before the dataset is limited that maybe not be really sufficient analysis to depend on to know the “Good” quality wines, It maybe helps only the “Average” quality wines producers to apply such analysis. Here the most interesting finding and may help in a future analysis that alcohol & sulphate make better wine quality. For future analysis may add more data to this dataset to get enough useful information to produce high-quality red wine and expand on the analysis of alcohol&sulphate may lead to perfect quality.
